    {
      "id": "meta-axioms-group",
      "type": "group",
      "x": -3560,
      "y": -7015,
      "width": 1700,
      "height": 420,
      "label": "Axioms (Irreducible Primaries)"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-existence",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Existence Exists\n\nThe irreducible starting point: *there is something rather than nothing.* \"Existence\" is the widest of all concepts \u2014 it subsumes every entity, action, attribute, and relationship.\n\nThis axiom cannot be proved \u2014 proof presupposes it. It is validated **ostensively**: by pointing to reality. Any act of perception already contains it. To deny it is to use it \u2014 the denier must exist to make the denial, must use concepts that refer to existents, must presuppose a world in which denial is possible.\n\n\"We start as philosophers where we began as babies, at the only place there is to begin: by looking at the world.\" \u2014 Peikoff, OPAR\n\nRand: *\"Existence exists \u2014 and the act of grasping that statement implies two corollary axioms: that something exists which one perceives and that one exists possessing consciousness.\"*\n\n**Status:** Axiom (perceptual self-evidency, implicit from the first sensation)\n**Validation:** Ostensive \u2014 look at reality\n**Denial is self-refuting:** To say \"nothing exists\" is to assert something, from somewhere, using concepts \u2014 all of which presuppose existence",
      "x": -3540,
      "y": -6995,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "1"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-consciousness",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Consciousness Exists\n\nYou are aware \u2014 and awareness is always awareness *of something.* Consciousness is \"the faculty of perceiving that which exists.\" It is not inherent in existence as such (a world without conscious organisms is possible), but it is inherent in your *grasp* of existence.\n\n\"There is something \u2014 *of which I am aware*.\" This recognition is implicit in every act of cognition.\n\nA consciousness with nothing to be conscious of is a contradiction. A consciousness conscious of nothing but itself is a contradiction \u2014 \"before it could identify itself as consciousness, it had to be conscious of something.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nAgainst Descartes: \"I think therefore I am\" is true, but taking it as the starting point implies you must infer existence from consciousness. In metaphysical fact, existence comes first \u2014 you cannot be aware before something exists. Existence and consciousness are grasped simultaneously, but existence has metaphysical priority.\n\n**Status:** Axiom (implicit once the child differentiates inner from outer world)\n**Validation:** Ostensive \u2014 the fact that you are perceiving\n**Denial is self-refuting:** To deny consciousness is to exercise it",
      "x": -2960,
      "y": -6995,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "1"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-identity",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## A is A (The Law of Identity)\n\nTo be is to be *something* \u2014 to have a nature, to possess identity. A thing is itself. Every existent has specific attributes and no others.\n\nRand's formulation: **\"Existence is identity.\"** Not \"existence *has* identity\" \u2014 which would suggest identity is separable from existence, like paint from a house. To be *is* to be something. Existence and identity are indivisible.\n\n\"Existence\" differentiates a thing from nothing (it *is* vs. it *is not*). \"Identity\" differentiates one thing from another (it is *this* vs. it is *that*). Two perspectives on the same indivisible fact.\n\nThe law of identity is the foundation of all logic, all science, all inferential knowledge. \"You couldn't do logic if you didn't have the rule of non-contradiction. If you didn't care about non-contradiction, any series of steps whatsoever would be valid \u2014 but they wouldn't correspond to reality.\" \u2014 Tew\n\nFirst explicitly identified by Antonius Andreas (medieval), though implicit in everything Aristotle does.\n\n**Status:** Axiom (implicit once the child differentiates *this* object from *that*)\n**Validation:** Ostensive \u2014 everything you perceive is something specific\n**Denial is self-refuting:** To deny identity is to assert that the denial is *something* \u2014 a specific claim with a specific meaning",
      "x": -2380,
      "y": -6995,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "1"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-entity",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Entity (Axiomatic Concept)\n\nEntities constitute the content of the world men perceive \u2014 there is nothing else to observe. An entity is a solid thing with perceivable shape (rock, person, table). By extension: solar systems, corporations, subatomic particles \u2014 all reducible to combinations or aspects of entities in the primary sense.\n\nAll other categories of being \u2014 qualities, quantities, relationships, actions \u2014 are merely *aspects of entities.* There is no \"red\" apart from the thing that is red. No \"walking\" apart from the creature that walks. **There are no floating actions; there are only actions performed by entities.**\n\nThe child grasps \"entity\" before \"identity\" \u2014 he must first perceive that objects exist (integrating sensations into percepts of things) before he can distinguish *this* object from *that.*\n\nEntity + Identity \u2192 the foundation for grasping Causality.\n\n**Status:** Axiomatic concept (presupposed by all subsequent cognition, but not itself a basic axiom)\n**Key principle:** \"Action\" is the name for what entities do \u2014 actions have no existence apart from the entities that perform them",
      "x": -2860,
      "y": -6515,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 340
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-corollaries-group",
      "type": "group",
      "x": -3660,
      "y": -6095,
      "width": 2700,
      "height": 500,
      "label": "Corollaries (Self-evident implications of the axioms)"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-primacy",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Primacy of Existence\n\nExistence comes first. Things are what they are **independent of consciousness** \u2014 of anyone's perceptions, images, ideas, or feelings. Consciousness is a dependent: its function is not to create or control existence, but to perceive it. \"The mind does not create the world. The mind identifies and is aware of the world.\" \u2014 Tew\n\nFrom the outset, consciousness presents itself as a faculty of perceiving an object, not of creating or changing it. A child may hate his food and refuse to look at it \u2014 but his inner state does not erase his dinner.\n\nThe opposite \u2014 **primacy of consciousness** \u2014 holds that consciousness creates reality. Three versions:\n- **Supernatural:** God's consciousness created existence (religion)\n- **Social:** A group's consciousness shapes reality (collectivism, consensus)\n- **Personal:** Each man's consciousness controls reality for him (subjectivism, Protagoras)\n\nAll are the same essential error. \"If existence exists, then it has metaphysical primacy. It is not a derivative or 'manifestation' of some true reality at its root. It *is* reality. As such, its elements are uncreated and eternal, and its laws, immutable.\" \u2014 Peikoff\n\n**Epistemological implication:** Knowledge of existence can only be gained by **extrospection** \u2014 by observing reality. No appeal to feelings, intuitions, or revelations as sources of knowledge about the world.\n\n*Derives from: Existence + Consciousness (existence is the object; consciousness is the faculty that perceives it \u2014 the object is primary)*",
      "x": -3640,
      "y": -6065,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 450
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-causality",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Law of Causality\n\nThe law of identity applied to action. Every entity has a specific nature \u2014 and must act in accordance with that nature. It cannot act apart from its nature (apart from its nature, a thing is nothing) or against it (A is A; contradictions are impossible).\n\n\"In any given set of circumstances, there is only one action possible to an entity, the action expressive of its identity. This is the action it will take, the action that is caused and necessitated by its nature.\" \u2014 Peikoff\n\nCrucial distinctions:\n- **Entities cause actions** \u2014 not actions causing other actions. It is not the *motion* of a billiard ball that produces effects; it is the *billiard ball* (substitute an egg \u2014 different effects).\n- **Not every entity has a cause** \u2014 the universe as a whole is eternal and uncaused (there is nothing outside totality to act as cause). What is caused is *action.*\n- **Does not require mechanical determinism** \u2014 an entity's nature determines what responses are *available* to it, not necessarily which single response must occur. This is crucial for compatibility with free will: a volitional consciousness has a specific identity that *includes* the capacity for choice.\n\n\"Every action has a cause (the cause is the nature of the entity which acts); and the same cause leads to the same effect.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nCausality is a fact independent of consciousness \u2014 not imposed by God (argument from design) nor a subjective mental form (Kant). It is inherent in being *qua* being.\n\n*Derives from: Identity + Entity (entity has a nature \u2192 must act accordingly)*",
      "x": -3080,
      "y": -6065,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 450
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-non-contradiction",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Law of Non-Contradiction\n\nA thing cannot be A and non-A at the same time and in the same respect. \"A leaf cannot be a stone at the same time, it cannot be all red and all green at the same time, it cannot freeze and burn at the same time.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nThis is the **epistemological** tool derived from the **metaphysical** law of identity. Identity is about reality (things are what they are); non-contradiction is about thought (your identifications must not contradict each other).\n\nBecause everything is what it is, there are no contradictions *in reality.* Therefore, if your conclusions contradict each other, at least one of them fails to correspond to reality. \"Contradictions exist only in faulty identification.\"\n\nNon-contradiction makes logic possible \u2014 it is what allows step-by-step cognitive processes to track reality. Without it, \"any series of steps whatsoever would be valid, but they wouldn't correspond to reality.\" \u2014 Tew\n\nObjectivist logic involves two complementary practices:\n- **Reduction** (correspondence) \u2014 trace your abstraction back to perceptual reality\n- **Integration** (coherence) \u2014 check that it fits with everything else you know\n\nThese never conflict, because reality coheres. \"All truths cohere because reality coheres. Reality is one; truth is one.\" \u2014 Tew\n\n*Derives from: Identity (the epistemological application of A is A)*",
      "x": -2520,
      "y": -6065,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 450
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-permanence",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Material Permanence\n\nIf existence exists, then entities cannot be created from nothing or annihilated into nothing. They may change attributes, split, merge, transform \u2014 but cannot come from or become *nonexistence.* \"Nothing does not exist\" is a core Objectivist premise.\n\n\"'Creation' does not (and metaphysically cannot) mean the power to bring something into existence out of nothing. 'Creation' means the power to bring into existence an arrangement of natural elements that had not existed before.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nThe universe is a **plenum** \u2014 solidly packed, no void, no empty space. \"There is no such thing as nothing. The universe is all there is. There's nothing outside the universe. There are no gaps inside the universe.\" \u2014 Tew (tracing to Parmenides)\n\nSpace is not a container into which things are placed \u2014 it is a **relational concept** among things (Aristotelian vs. Platonic). \"There are only things. Space is just a relationship between things.\" \u2014 Tew\n\nWhen we say \"there's nothing in that room,\" we mean nothing *relevant to our purpose* \u2014 not a literal void. \"Nothing\" is epistemological shorthand, not a metaphysical entity.\n\nConsequence: The universe is eternal \u2014 \"its elements are uncreated and eternal\" (Peikoff). No creation ex nihilo. No annihilation into nothing.\n\n*Derives from: Existence (existence exists \u2192 nonexistence does not exist)*",
      "x": -1960,
      "y": -6065,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 450
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-senses-valid",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Validity of the Senses\n\nThe validity of the senses is an axiom \u2014 a corollary of the fact of consciousness. If man is conscious of that which is, then his means of awareness *are* means of awareness, i.e., are valid. To attack the senses is to attack consciousness itself.\n\nThe senses **cannot err.** They respond automatically to stimuli via causal law \u2014 \"they have no power of choice, no power to invent, distort, or deceive.\" Error arises only at the conceptual level, in *inferences* drawn from sensory data. If a boy sees a man in a red suit and infers Santa Claus, his senses made no error \u2014 his conclusion did.\n\nA \"sensory illusion\" (stick appearing bent in water) is not a perceptual error but a testament to the senses' reliability \u2014 they faithfully report the full physical context, including how light refracts through water.\n\n**Form vs. Object:** Sensory qualities (color, sound, smell) derive from the interaction of external objects with our sense organs. They are neither purely \"in the object\" nor purely \"in the mind\" \u2014 they are **object-as-perceived.** A color-blind man and a normal-sighted man perceive the same object in different *forms* \u2014 neither is wrong, neither contradicts the other.\n\nRand: *\"The task of man's senses is to give him the evidence of existence, but the task of identifying it belongs to his reason. His senses tell him only that something is, but what it is must be learned by his mind.\"*\n\nDifferences in sensory form have no consequences for cognitive content \u2014 beings with radically different senses would reach the same scientific conclusions about reality.\n\n*Derives from: Consciousness (if you are conscious, your means of consciousness are valid)*",
      "x": -1400,
      "y": -6065,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 450
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-volition",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Volition (Free Will)\n\nVolition is an **irreducible metaphysical fact** \u2014 a corollary of the axiom of consciousness. Not every consciousness has free will, but every *fallible, conceptual* consciousness must. An organism that can err in its identifications must have the power to initiate or suspend the cognitive process; otherwise error has no meaning.\n\nThis is a fact about the **nature of reality**, not merely about how man happens to think. Volition belongs to the same metaphysical stratum as causality, identity, and entity \u2014 it is part of what exists.\n\n**Validation is introspective, not rationalistic.** The self-refuting argument against determinism is a useful corollary, but it is not the *proof*. The proof is that you can look inward and *see* yourself choosing \u2014 direct, firsthand observation of your own freedom of choice. Free will is as directly observable as any other existent.\n\n**Two errors block understanding:** (1) *Lack of introspection* \u2014 people never examine their own consciousness, so the reality of choice is alien to them; (2) *Rationalism* \u2014 they deduce how consciousness *must* work from arbitrary premises about physical causality rather than observing how it actually works. There is nothing in reality that excludes the influence of consciousness on the material world, and nothing that requires the actions of consciousness to be the linear result of prior causes.\n\n**Compatibility with causality.** The law of causality says entities act according to their nature. It does not require that all action be mechanistic. Definite does not mean linear, and identity is not linearity. Man's nature *includes* the capacity for choice. Causality describes the *form* of action (entity-driven); volition is a *type* of entity-driven action.\n\n**Determinism is self-refuting.** If all ideas are necessitated by prior physical causes, the determinist cannot claim his conclusion is *true* \u2014 he had no choice but to reach it, rational or not. But note: this argument is a *consequence* of free will's existence, not its proof.\n\nRand: **\"The faculty of reason IS the faculty of volition.\"** This removes free will from mysticism (Kant's noumenal freedom, Libertarian miracle-agency) and grounds it in man's this-worldly, natural identity. Free will is not a violation of natural law but an *expression* of it \u2014 the way a rational entity acts.\n\n*Derives from: Consciousness (corollary \u2014 a fallible conceptual consciousness must be volitional)*\n*Compatible with: Causality (entity acts according to its nature; man's nature includes choice)*\n*Epistemological application: see Epistemology \u2192 \"Volition: The Epistemological Locus\"*",
      "x": -840,
      "y": -6065,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 450,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-absolute-group",
      "type": "group",
      "x": -3260,
      "y": -5465,
      "width": 1300,
      "height": 480,
      "label": "Culmination"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-metaphysically-given",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## The Metaphysically Given as Absolute\n\nThe culminating principle of Objectivist metaphysics: **no alternative to a fact of reality is possible or imaginable.** Every metaphysically given fact is *necessary* \u2014 necessitated by the nature of existence and therefore unchangeable by any agency.\n\nAs soon as one says of any metaphysically given fact \"it is\" \u2014 the whole Objectivist metaphysics is implicit:\n- It is what it is \u2192 **(Identity)**\n- It is lawful, inherent in the identities of entities \u2192 **(Causality)**\n- It is independent of consciousness \u2192 **(Primacy of Existence)**\n- It has to be; no alternative is possible \u2192 **(Necessity)**\n\nA fact is \"necessary\" if its nonexistence would involve a contradiction. To be is to be necessary (for metaphysically given facts). \"To be\" is \"to be something\" is \"to act accordingly\" is \"to be necessary.\"\n\n**The metaphysically given vs. the man-made:**\n- *Metaphysically given* (facts of nature): must be **accepted** \u2014 not evaluated, not praised or blamed. \"They are, were, will be, and have to be.\"\n- *Man-made* (products of choice): must be **evaluated** \u2014 accepted or rejected and changed when necessary.\n\nTwo errors from confusing them:\n1. Treating the man-made as immutable (\"you can't fight city hall\" \u2014 sanctioning any status quo)\n2. Treating the metaphysically given as alterable \u2014 the fallacy of **\"rewriting reality\"** (condemning life because pain is possible, rebelling against death, demanding non-sensory knowledge)\n\n\"Respect for reality does not guarantee success in every endeavor. But it does guarantee that, if one fails, he will not harbor a metaphysical grudge.\" \u2014 Peikoff\n\nThe rejection of this principle leads to the false mind-body dichotomy: \"my dream vs. the actual which thwarts it.\" Acceptance leads to harmony: conforming to reality is not defeat but the precondition of success.\n\n*Derives from: All axioms and corollaries integrated*",
      "x": -3240,
      "y": -5435,
      "width": 1260,
      "height": 430,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-mind-body",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## The Mind as Action of the Body\n\nThe mind is neither independent of the body (idealism) nor reducible to specific physical matter (materialism). It is **the highest level of action involved in the maintenance of the body** \u2014 the rational, volitional aspect of the life process.\n\nTwo failed routes to life after death expose the mind's true nature:\n1. **Mind floats free of the body** \u2014 impossible, because awareness depends on the senses, which require physical sense organs. Turn them off and consciousness disappears.\n2. **Mind is tied to specific bodily matter** \u2014 impossible, because the body's matter constantly changes (eating, cell regeneration, growth) while the mind endures. Reconstructing the body from identical matter would not restore the same consciousness.\n\nThe reconciliation: mind is tied not to the body's *stuff* but to the body's *process* \u2014 the ongoing action of expending energy to acquire energy, replacing matter to maintain the form. Ship of Theseus: you are not the planks but the action of replacing the planks.\n\nBecause mind is action along a temporal continuum, **continuity is essential to identity.** Once the action stops (death), restarting biological processes creates a metaphysically new instance of action \u2014 a separate being, not you. Life is one and done.\n\n*Derives from: Consciousness (consciousness is an action, not a free-floating substance); Entity (actions have no existence apart from the entities that perform them); Causality (life is self-sustaining action)*\n*Source: Charles Tew, \"Life after Death Is Impossible\" (vjdVZBbuxMQ)*",
      "x": -1860,
      "y": -5435,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 430
    },
    {
      "id": "meta-idealism-materialism",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Neither Idealism nor Materialism\n\nObjectivism rejects both classic metaphysical errors:\n\n**Idealism** (Plato, Augustine, Hegel): Reality is ultimately spiritual/mental \u2014 a transcendent consciousness creates or underlies existence. This is the primacy of consciousness \u2192 \"consciousness without existence.\" Leads to mysticism (\"mystics of spirit\").\n\n**Materialism** (Democritus, Hobbes, Marx, Skinner): Consciousness is a myth or useless byproduct \u2014 only physical matter is real. This is \"existence without consciousness.\" Leads to a different mysticism (\"mystics of muscle\") \u2014 rejecting the faculty of reason itself.\n\nBoth accept a false alternative invented by idealists: consciousness *vs.* science. Materialists simply pick the other side.\n\nThe **supernatural** is an assault on every axiom: a creator God violates primacy of existence; omnipotence violates identity; miracles violate causality; the \"infinite\" violates the finitude required by A is A. \"Every argument commonly offered for the notion of God leads to a contradiction of the axiomatic concepts of philosophy.\" \u2014 Peikoff\n\nThe truth: Consciousness is an attribute of certain living organisms, wholly natural, observable by introspection, with a specific nature and life-sustaining function. It is neither supernatural nor reducible to matter. \"The soul is not man's ticket to another reality; it is a development of and within nature.\" \u2014 Aristotle via Peikoff\n\nObjectivism: existence exists, *and* consciousness exists. Both are real. Neither is derivative of the other. The relationship is: existence is primary, consciousness perceives it.\n\n*Relates to: Primacy of Existence, Consciousness*",
      "x": -1280,
      "y": -5435,
      "width": 500,
      "height": 430,
      "color": "3"
    },
    {
      "id": "epist-wrapper-group",
