      "height": 480,
      "label": "The Virtues"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-integration-group",
      "type": "group",
      "x": -1200,
      "y": 930,
      "width": 2320,
      "height": 460,
      "label": "Integration"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-culmination-group",
      "type": "group",
      "x": -1000,
      "y": 1490,
      "width": 1200,
      "height": 460,
      "label": "Culmination & Bridge to Politics"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-fundamental-alternative",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## The Fundamental Alternative: Existence or Non-Existence\n\nOnly living organisms face the alternative of existence or non-existence \u2014 and this is what makes the concept of \"value\" possible. A rock cannot go out of existence *qua rock*; it merely changes form. But a living organism must continually act to sustain its own life \u2014 or perish.\n\nLife is a process of self-sustaining and self-generated action. An organism that fails to act in accordance with its nature ceases to exist as a living organism. This is the fundamental alternative that gives rise to all goals, all values, all purposes.\n\nThe \"immortal robot\" argument: a being that could not be destroyed, that faced no alternative of existence or nonexistence, would have no values \u2014 nothing to gain or lose. It is only because life is *conditional* \u2014 because living organisms can fail \u2014 that the concept \"value\" has any meaning.\n\n\"It is only the concept of 'Life' that makes the concept of 'Value' possible.\" \u2014 Rand\n\n*Derives from: Existence Exists [metaphysics], Entity [metaphysics], Causality [metaphysics] \u2014 living entities are goal-directed because they face the alternative*",
      "x": -720,
      "y": -1910,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 440
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-life-standard",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Life as the Standard of Value\n\nLife is not merely what makes values possible \u2014 it is the standard by which they are measured. \"Value\" is that which one acts to gain and/or keep; the ultimate value, the final goal that sets the standard for all lesser goals, is the organism's own life.\n\nThe good is that which promotes the organism's life; the evil is that which threatens or destroys it. This is not a moral commandment but a metaphysical identification of the relationship between living organisms and values.\n\nThe standard is not a \"desire to live\" (one could desire anything); it is the objective requirements of life itself \u2014 the factual conditions an organism's nature demands for its survival. Ethics is thus grounded in biology: the nature of a living organism determines what is good or evil *for it.*\n\n*Derives from: The Fundamental Alternative \u2014 life-or-death is what makes values possible and necessary; Causality [metaphysics] \u2014 living entities act to sustain themselves*",
      "x": -1040,
      "y": -1330,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-choice-to-live",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## The Choice to Live\n\nMan, unlike plants and animals, has no automatic code of values \u2014 he must choose them, starting with the most fundamental: the choice to live. This choice is pre-moral: it cannot itself be proved or derived from ethics, because it is the precondition of all valuation.\n\nThe choice is implicit in every purposeful action. Every time a man sets a goal, takes a step, or makes a plan, he is operationally committed to his own life \u2014 whether he acknowledges it or not.\n\nGiven this choice, ethics becomes absolute. The structure is: *if* you choose to live, *then* a specific, objective code of values follows. The \"if\" is not arbitrary \u2014 it is the foundation that makes the \"then\" possible. One is free to reject life \u2014 but not free to reject life and expect to flourish.\n\n*Derives from: Life as the Standard \u2014 the standard gives the choice its content; Volition [epistemology] \u2014 the choice is volitional, not automatic*",
      "x": -400,
      "y": -1330,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-life-qua-rational",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Man's Life Qua Rational Being as the Standard\n\nThe standard of value is not mere physical survival at any cost \u2014 it is \"man's life *qua* rational being\": the kind of life proper to a being whose means of survival is reason. This distinction is crucial.\n\nA man who \"survives\" by predation, fraud, or parasitism is not living *qua man*. A man who abandons reason and lives moment to moment by range-of-the-moment impulses has abandoned the standard. \"Life qua man\" means: long-range, principled, reason-guided living \u2014 the kind of life that includes productive achievement, self-esteem, and the rational enjoyment of values.\n\nMan has a specific nature \u2014 and that nature determines the specific form of life that constitutes his good. Man's life is not the life of a dog, or an amoeba, or an angel. It is the life of a rational animal who must think, produce, and choose.\n\n*Derives from: Life as the Standard \u2014 specifies the standard for man; Identity [metaphysics] \u2014 man has a specific nature; Man: The Rational Animal [epistemology] \u2014 man's nature defines the standard*",
      "x": -1040,
      "y": -750,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "5"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-values-objective",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Values as Objective\n\nValues are neither intrinsic (existing in objects independent of any valuer) nor subjective (created by whims independent of reality). They are **objective**: determined by the relationship between the facts of reality and the requirements of the valuer's life.\n\nThe intrinsicist says: \"This is good because God/Nature/Duty decrees it \u2014 regardless of what it does to you.\" The subjectivist says: \"This is good because I feel it/want it \u2014 regardless of the facts.\" The objectivist says: \"This is good because it actually sustains my life as a rational being \u2014 as identified by reason from the facts.\"\n\nAn objective value is not \"whatever one happens to value\" but \"that which one *ought* to value, given the facts of reality and the requirements of one's life.\" The method of identifying objective values is reason \u2014 the same faculty that identifies objective facts.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 rational evaluation determines objective values; Objectivity [epistemology] \u2014 the concept of objectivity applies to values as to all knowledge*",
      "x": -400,
      "y": -750,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "3"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-rationality",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Rationality: The Cardinal Virtue\n\nIf man's life qua rational being is the standard, and reason is man's sole means of survival, then the fundamental virtue is *rationality*: the recognition and acceptance of reason as one's only source of knowledge, one's only guide to action, and one's only judge of values.\n\nRationality means: full mental focus, a commitment to awareness as a way of life, the refusal to evade any fact. It means: never placing any consideration above reality \u2014 not feelings, not wishes, not social pressure, not authority.\n\nAll other virtues \u2014 independence, integrity, honesty, justice, productiveness, pride \u2014 are aspects and applications of rationality. Rationality is not one virtue among equals; it is the root from which all others grow. A man can fail at any particular virtue only by failing first at rationality \u2014 by evading some fact that the virtue requires him to face.\n\n*Derives from: Man's Life Qua Rational Being \u2014 life qua man requires reason; The Choice to Live \u2014 if you choose to live, reason is the means; Reason [epistemology] \u2014 reason is man's means of survival*",
      "x": -1360,
      "y": -190,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 400,
      "color": "5"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-rational-self-interest",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Rational Self-Interest\n\nEach man is the proper beneficiary of his own moral action \u2014 he ought to pursue his own life and happiness as his highest purpose. \"Rational\" is the critical qualifier: self-interest means interest as identified by reason, not by whim, impulse, or predation.\n\nThree positions on the beneficiary question: (1) **Altruism** \u2014 sacrifice yourself to others; (2) **Predation** \u2014 sacrifice others to yourself; (3) **Rational egoism** \u2014 pursue your own life by rational means, trading value for value with others. Only the third is consistent with man's nature as a rational being.\n\nThe trader principle follows: deal with others by voluntary exchange, to mutual benefit. Never seek the unearned \u2014 neither in matter nor in spirit.\n\n\"I swear by my life and my love of it that I will never live for the sake of another man, nor ask another man to live for mine.\" \u2014 Galt's Oath\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 rational pursuit of one's own life; Man as an End in Himself \u2014 each man is the proper beneficiary*",
      "x": -760,
      "y": -190,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 400,
      "color": "5"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-man-end-himself",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Man as an End in Himself\n\nEach individual is an end in himself \u2014 not a means to the ends of others. This is the ethical corollary of reason being an attribute of the individual: no man can think for another, live for another, or substitute his consciousness for another's.\n\nThe rejection of self-sacrifice does not mean indifference to others. It means that concern for others is a *value* \u2014 chosen and earned \u2014 not a duty imposed by default. One properly values others in proportion to the values they represent, by the standard of one's own life.\n\nThe opposite view \u2014 that man exists to serve others (society, God, the collective) \u2014 is the ethics of altruism. It treats man as a sacrificial animal whose purpose is to provide for others' welfare. This is incompatible with man's nature as a rational, volitional being with his own life to sustain.\n\n*Derives from: Rational Self-Interest \u2014 the beneficiary question answered*",
      "x": -160,
      "y": -190,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 400,
      "color": "5"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-independence",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Independence\n\nOne's acceptance of the responsibility of forming one's own judgments and of living by the work of one's own mind. The independent man is oriented to reality, not to other men \u2014 he does not accept ideas on faith, authority, or social pressure.\n\nThe opposite is the \"second-hander\": one who places other people's judgments above his own perception of reality, who lives through others \u2014 seeking approval, following the crowd, substituting consensus for cognition.\n\nIndependence does not mean isolation or refusal to learn from others. It means: in any collaboration, one's own rational judgment is the final court of appeal. One can learn from a teacher, but one must understand the lesson \u2014 not merely memorize and obey. \"Reason is an attribute of the individual.\" \u2014 Peikoff\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 first-hand thinking as an aspect of full commitment to reason*",
      "x": -1520,
      "y": 390,
      "width": 480,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-integrity",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Integrity\n\nLoyalty to one's rational principles in action \u2014 the refusal to permit a breach between one's convictions and one's behavior. Integrity is the recognition that one cannot fake one's own consciousness \u2014 that acting against one's knowledge is self-destruction.\n\nThe man of integrity does not sacrifice his convictions to social pressure, economic convenience, or emotional impulse. He recognizes that \"in any compromise between food and poison, it is only death that can win. In any compromise between good and evil, it is only evil that can profit.\"\n\nIntegrity does not mean dogmatic rigidity \u2014 if one discovers that one's principles are wrong, reason demands revision. But it means: one does not abandon a principle one knows to be right merely because acting on it is difficult or unpopular.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 loyalty to rational principles as an aspect of commitment to reason*",
      "x": -1010,
      "y": 390,
      "width": 480,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-honesty",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Honesty\n\nThe refusal to fake reality \u2014 the recognition that the unreal is unreal and can have no value. Honesty is not primarily a social virtue (\"don't lie to others\") but a metaphysical one: don't attempt to gain values by faking the facts of reality.\n\nThe con man who gains wealth by fraud has not gained a genuine value \u2014 he has created a structure built on unreality, which must eventually collapse. He has attempted to make reality other than it is, which is metaphysically impossible.\n\nHonesty includes honesty with oneself \u2014 the refusal to evade facts one has perceived, the refusal to pretend that one does not know what one knows. This is why honesty is an aspect of rationality: evasion is the fundamental form of dishonesty.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 the refusal to fake reality as an aspect of commitment to reason*",
      "x": -500,
      "y": 390,
      "width": 480,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-justice",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Justice\n\nRationality in the evaluation of men \u2014 the practice of judging character and actions objectively, and of granting to each what he has earned. Justice requires both the recognition of virtue and the condemnation of vice.\n\nThe trader principle in human relationships: deal with others by exchanging value for value, by mutual consent. Never seek the unearned \u2014 neither in matter nor in spirit. Never grant the undeserved. Judge, and be prepared to be judged.\n\nThe **sanction of the victim**: the moral error of willingly empowering evil by accepting unearned guilt. When good men grant moral legitimacy to those who would destroy them, they become accomplices in their own destruction. Justice demands that one withhold this sanction.\n\nJustice does not mean mercilessness. Forgiveness is proper when someone demonstrates genuine change. But \"mercy\" to evil at the expense of the good \u2014 excusing the guilty because punishment is \"harsh\" \u2014 is injustice.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 rationality in evaluating men as an aspect of commitment to reason*",
      "x": 10,
      "y": 390,
      "width": 480,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-productiveness",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Productiveness\n\nThe adjustment of nature to man \u2014 the process of creating material values by reshaping the natural world to serve human life. Productiveness is the recognition that nature gives nothing for free and that man survives by transforming his environment through the application of reason.\n\nProductiveness requires a **central purpose in life** \u2014 a long-range productive goal that integrates and organizes one's lesser goals and daily activities. A man without a central purpose is adrift, regardless of how busy he appears.\n\nWork is not a necessary evil or punishment \u2014 it is the fundamental expression of man's nature as a being who survives by thought and production. The spiritual meaning of productive work is that it is the process of shaping one's environment to match one's values \u2014 making the world one's own.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 the adjustment of nature to man as an aspect of commitment to reason*",
      "x": 520,
      "y": 390,
      "width": 480,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-pride",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Pride\n\nMoral ambitiousness \u2014 the commitment to achieving one's own moral perfection. As productiveness is the shaping of nature to serve man, pride is the shaping of one's own soul to match one's moral ideal.\n\nMoral perfection does not mean infallibility \u2014 it means unbreached rationality: the refusal to accept any code of irrational virtues impossible to practice, and the consistent practice of the virtues one knows to be rational. A man of pride does not accept unearned guilt, does not tolerate unexplained defects in his character, and does not give up the effort of moral self-improvement.\n\nPride is the crown of the virtues \u2014 the virtue that presupposes and integrates all the others. It is the emotional reward of a life lived in accordance with one's own rational standards: the right to regard oneself as one's highest value.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 moral ambitiousness as an aspect of commitment to reason*",
      "x": 1030,
      "y": 390,
      "width": 480,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-virtue-practical",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Virtue as Practical\n\nThe alleged conflict between the moral and the practical is a false dichotomy produced by the mind-body split. In Objectivist ethics, virtue IS the practical: it is the means by which man sustains his life and achieves his happiness.\n\nThe immoral is the impractical. Evil is metaphysically impotent \u2014 it can destroy but cannot create, can parasitize but cannot produce. A man who evades reality may appear to gain in the short term, but his gains are built on unreality and must collapse.\n\n\"The practical man\" who scorns morality and \"the moral man\" who scorns worldly success are two sides of the same counterfeit coin \u2014 both accept the premise that virtue requires sacrifice. It does not. Virtue is the *means* to life and happiness, not an obstacle to them.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 virtue is the means to life, not a sacrifice*",
      "x": -1160,
      "y": 970,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-harmony-interests",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## The Harmony of Rational Interests\n\nThere are no conflicts of interest among rational men. Men who pursue rational values by rational means do not clash \u2014 they trade to mutual benefit. Conflicts arise only from irrationality: when men seek the unearned, pursue contradictory \"values,\" or resort to force or fraud.\n\nThe alleged \"conflicts\" that supposedly require sacrifice \u2014 competition for jobs, resources, romantic partners \u2014 are not conflicts among *rational* interests. Two men competing for the same job are not in conflict: the better man earns the position, and the other seeks elsewhere. The conflict model presupposes a zero-sum world, which is the world of the looter, not the trader.\n\nThis principle makes a free society possible. If men's interests necessarily conflicted, social life would require perpetual sacrifice. Because rational interests *harmonize*, a society of free men trading voluntarily is not merely possible but natural.\n\n*Derives from: Justice \u2014 just men trade to mutual benefit; Rational Self-Interest \u2014 rational egoists do not clash*",
      "x": -580,
      "y": 970,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-force-evil",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## The Initiation of Physical Force as Evil\n\nThe initiation of physical force is the practical negation of reason. A man at gunpoint can still think \u2014 but he cannot act on his thinking. Since reason is man's means of survival, and force prevents a man from acting on reason, the initiation of force is the fundamental anti-life act.\n\nForce and mind are opposites. Where force rules, reason is impotent; where reason rules, force is unnecessary. The man who resorts to force has abandoned the tool of a rational being \u2014 persuasion, trade, voluntary agreement \u2014 and substituted the tool of an animal: physical compulsion.\n\nOnly *retaliatory* force \u2014 used in response to the initiation of force \u2014 is moral. The right of self-defense is the corollary of the right to life. This principle is the bridge from ethics to politics: the sole purpose of a proper government is to protect individual rights by placing retaliatory force under objective control.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality \u2014 force negates the mind; The Harmony of Rational Interests \u2014 force is the negation of rational interaction*",
      "x": 0,
      "y": 970,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 400,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-happiness",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Happiness as the Moral Purpose\n\nHappiness is \"a state of noncontradictory joy \u2014 a joy without penalty or guilt, a joy that does not clash with any of one's values and does not work for one's own destruction.\" It is the emotional state that results from the achievement of one's rational values.\n\nHappiness is not the *standard* of value \u2014 that is man's life. It is the *purpose*: the emotional reward of living morally. The distinction matters: using happiness as the standard leads to hedonism (whatever feels good is good); using life as the standard and happiness as the purpose means that genuine happiness follows only from rational values.\n\nThe moral-practical unity means that happiness is the *normal condition* of a rational man \u2014 not a miraculous exception but the natural consequence of living in accordance with reality. Because the universe is open to man's achievement, happiness is the metaphysically to-be-expected for those who live rationally.\n\n*Derives from: The Benevolent Universe Premise \u2014 success is the metaphysically normal; Rational Self-Interest \u2014 happiness is the purpose of moral action; Emotions as Products of Ideas [epistemology] \u2014 happiness is an emotional state following from values*",
      "x": -980,
      "y": 1530,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 400,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-benevolent-universe",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## The Benevolent Universe Premise\n\nThe universe is not hostile or rigged against man \u2014 it is *open* to human achievement. Success, not suffering, is the metaphysically to-be-expected for a rational being. This is not the claim that the universe \"cares\" about man or guarantees success \u2014 it means that reality is lawful, knowable, and amenable to rational action.\n\nEvil is metaphysically impotent. It cannot build, create, or produce \u2014 it can only destroy and parasitize. Evil can subsist only by leeching from the good: the \"sanction of the victim.\" The good is self-sufficient; evil depends entirely on the good for its continued existence.\n\nMaintaining this premise requires sustained rational effort, and the difficulty varies with one's circumstances. But outside of extreme cases, it is always achievable. Even humor serves to reinforce it: laughter asserts that the irrational is abnormal and should not be taken as the standard of reality.\n\n*Derives from: Virtue as Practical \u2014 if virtue is the means to life, the universe is open to the virtuous*",
      "x": 580,
      "y": 970,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "eth-right-to-property",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Right to Property (Ethical Root)\n\nIf man must produce to live, and production requires the exercise of reason applied to nature, then man must have the right to keep, use, and dispose of the product of his effort. Without property rights, productiveness is rendered futile \u2014 the incentive to create is destroyed when the product can be seized.\n\nProperty is not a social convention but a moral requirement rooted in man's nature. The right to property is the right to the *action* of producing and to the *result* of that action. It is the implementation of the right to life in the material sphere.\n\nThis is the ethical root \u2014 the political elaboration (how property rights are defined, adjudicated, and protected by government) belongs to the politics canvas. The bridge: the initiation of force as evil implies that no one may seize another's product by force.\n\n*Derives from: Productiveness \u2014 if you must produce, you must keep the product; Man as an End in Himself \u2014 man's right to the product of his effort; The Initiation of Force as Evil \u2014 property rights protect against force*",
      "x": -380,
      "y": 1530,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 380,
      "color": "3"
    },
    {
      "id": "pol-wrapper-group",
