      "height": 540,
      "label": "The Standard"
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-32c85169e9a25f2c",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Man's Need for Art\n\nArt is a need of the mind \u2014 of man *qua* thinker and valuer. A conceptual consciousness requires the ultimate integration of its contents that only philosophy can provide: a view of existence as a whole. But philosophical principles are the widest of all abstractions \u2014 no one can hold such complexity in focus *as a sum.*\n\nThe chain of unit-economy: percepts are condensed into concepts; concepts are condensed into philosophy; and art condenses philosophy \u2014 by returning to the perceptual level, this time in a form impregnated with profound abstract meaning. Art gives man a concrete on which he can choose to focus, carrying with it the meaning of his whole view of life.\n\n\"Art is inextricably tied to man's survival \u2014 not to his physical survival, but to that on which his physical survival depends: to the preservation and survival of his consciousness.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nThis is why art has always existed among men, from prehistory to the present, and why animals have neither art nor any equivalent of it.\n\n*Derives from: Concept Formation [epistemology] \u2014 conceptual beings need to experience abstractions as concretes; Man: The Rational Animal [epistemology] \u2014 man's conceptual nature creates the need for art*",
      "x": 1590,
      "y": 3240,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-db225a92638bd5ea",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Art: Selective Re-Creation of Reality\n\n\"Art is a selective re-creation of reality according to an artist's metaphysical value-judgments.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nThe operative word is *selective.* Art is not reproduction, journalism, or photography. The artist does not report neutrally on \"the way things are\" \u2014 he re-creates reality from his own metaphysical perspective. He isolates what he regards as essential and integrates it into a new concrete that represents an embodied abstraction.\n\nAn art work tells man not that something *is*, but that it is *important.* \"Important\" is the esthetic criterion \u2014 distinct from the epistemological \"essential\" and the ethical \"good.\" Everything included in a work of art acquires metaphysical significance by the mere fact of being included. A cold sore on a painted goddess is not a medical fact \u2014 it is a metaphysical statement.\n\nThe role of art is not didactic. \"The basic purpose of art is *not* to teach, but to *show* \u2014 to hold up to man a concretized image of his nature and his place in the universe.\" \u2014 Rand. In life, one ignores the unimportant; in art, one omits it.\n\n*Derives from: Man's Need for Art \u2014 the need determines the nature of art*",
      "x": 1590,
      "y": 3840,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "5"
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-0989c426322aa062",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Metaphysical Value-Judgments\n\n\"The link between metaphysics and ethics\" \u2014 a category of questions that assumes in man's mind the function of value-judgments with the compelling power of a basic emotion. The fundamental questions: Is the universe intelligible? Can man find happiness? Does man possess the power of choice? Is man to be valued as good or despised as evil?\n\nThese are not ethical questions (\"By what rules should a man live?\") but logically prior ones (\"*Can* man live?\"). Metaphysics thus acts as man's \"value conditioner\" \u2014 by specifying what man can realistically aspire to, it tells him how to approach morality.\n\nThe artist, guided by his MVJs (explicit or otherwise), selects from the chaos of human experience those aspects he regards as indicative of the nature of the universe, then embodies them in a perceptual concrete. **Subject** expresses the artist's *metaphysics*; **style** expresses his *psycho-epistemology* \u2014 his view of consciousness and its proper method of functioning.\n\nA man's MVJs \"are involved in every moment of his life, in his every choice, decision and action.\" They must be available to him at all times \u2014 and available *as a sum.* This is precisely what art makes possible.\n\n*Derives from: Art as Selective Re-Creation \u2014 the artist selects according to his metaphysical value-judgments*",
      "x": 1290,
      "y": 4440,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 460,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-sense-of-life",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Sense of Life\n\n\"A pre-conceptual equivalent of metaphysics, an emotional, subconsciously integrated appraisal of man and of existence.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nFrom early childhood, an individual makes choices and reaches conclusions about concrete problems. These accumulate into an abstract sum \u2014 a sense of oneself and the world. A man who characteristically chooses to be mentally active develops a sense of efficacy and optimism; the opposite choice instills helplessness and malevolence.\n\nMost men hardly conceptualize metaphysical issues at all \u2014 they remain at the mercy of their inarticulate sense of life. A handful work to translate it into explicit philosophy. Those who succeed bring their conscious and subconscious into harmony; those who default may live tortured by the clash between avowed beliefs and basic feelings.\n\n\"It is the artist's sense of life that controls and integrates his work, directing the innumerable choices he has to make. It is the viewer's or reader's sense of life that responds to a work of art by a complex, yet automatic reaction of acceptance and approval, or rejection and condemnation.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nSense-of-life emotions, like all others, are explicable \u2014 and alterable, if the facts of reality so demand. Art is inherently philosophical because it must express some sense-of-life emotion, which can be identified and translated into explicit metaphysical value-judgments.\n\n*Derives from: Metaphysical Value-Judgments \u2014 sense of life is the subconscious form of MVJs; Emotions as Products of Ideas [epistemology] \u2014 sense of life is an emotional integration of metaphysical conclusions*",
      "x": 1890,
      "y": 4440,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 460,
      "color": "4"
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-2b6ac9a9f9b37fa0",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Psycho-Epistemological Function of Art\n\n\"Art brings man's concepts to the perceptual level of his consciousness and allows him to grasp them directly, as if they were percepts.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nThis is the crux of the Objectivist esthetics. Art completes the chain of unit-economy: percepts \u2192 concepts \u2192 philosophy \u2192 art *returns to percepts*, this time impregnated with abstract meaning. By converting abstractions into percepts, art integrates *and* objectifies metaphysics \u2014 making it external, \"out there,\" an existential fact rather than merely a content of consciousness.\n\nThis is an expression of the primacy of existence: consciousness cannot attain fulfillment within its own domain. To satisfy its deepest needs, it must return to its primary task \u2014 looking outward. To an entity whose essence is perception, there is no substitute for perception.\n\nTo a rational man, art that objectifies *his* metaphysics provides a unique inspiration \u2014 an indispensable source of emotional fuel: \"the life-giving fact of experiencing a moment of *metaphysical* joy \u2014 a moment of love for existence.\" Art is \"the technology of the soul\" \u2014 what the designer of a bridge is to engineering, the artist is to ethics. Art creates the final product. It builds the model.\n\n*Derives from: Art as Selective Re-Creation \u2014 art brings concepts to the perceptual level; Sense of Life \u2014 sense of life drives both creation and response; Primacy of Existence [metaphysics] \u2014 consciousness must return to perception*",
      "x": 1590,
      "y": 5080,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 440,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-romanticism",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Romanticism\n\n\"A category of art based on the recognition of the principle that man possesses the faculty of volition.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nThe Romantic school arose on the heels of the Enlightenment, when an Aristotelian sense of life dominated the culture \u2014 a subconscious confidence in man's mind, with capitalism as its political corollary. What united the Romanticists was the principle that man is self-directed and goal-directed; what they rejected was determinism.\n\n**Plot** is the literary expression of purposeful action: \"a purposeful progression of logically connected events leading to the resolution of a climax.\" Plot implies that *life* is logical \u2014 a man's choices shape his fate. **Characterization** is abstract projection: characters are \"larger than life,\" presenting essential human attributes in purer form \u2014 embodied universals, not reproductions of concretes.\n\n**Naturalism** is the opposite: determinism, plotlessness, statistics as the standard. By substituting \"what happens to happen\" for \"what counts about man,\" Naturalism negates art's essential function.\n\n**Romantic Realism** is Rand's synthesis: \"I am Romantic in the sense that I present men as they ought to be. I am Realistic in the sense that I place them here and now and on this earth.\" Romanticism is \"objectively the greatest achievement in art history.\"\n\n*Derives from: Volition [epistemology] \u2014 Romanticism is art based on recognition of volition; Metaphysical Value-Judgments \u2014 Romanticism affirms volition as metaphysically significant; Sense of Life \u2014 an Aristotelian sense of life gave rise to Romanticism*",
      "x": 1590,
      "y": 5700,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-humor",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Humor\n\n\"Humor is the denial of metaphysical significance to that which you laugh at.\" \u2014 Rand\n\nWhen you laugh at something, you declare it unreal, abnormal, insignificant. Humor is inherently destructive \u2014 and this is appropriate, provided it is aimed at what deserves destruction: evil, irrationality, and vice. To mock virtue is vicious; to mock vice is healthy.\n\nHumor reinforces the benevolent universe premise. By laughing at the irrational, one asserts that it is the exception, the abnormal \u2014 not the standard of reality. Comedy provides fuel by presenting the vicious in its proper light.\n\nWhat one finds funny reflects one's sense of life. A man with genuine values will not find funny a joke that mocks what he truly values, regardless of how cleverly it is constructed. \"If it's funny, it's funny\" is pseudo-objectivity \u2014 a refusal to recognize that comedy necessarily carries moral implications.\n\nAnti-rational humor \u2014 humor that requires suppressing logic to find amusing \u2014 is contemptible. Not all evil is appropriate material for comedy: actual manifestations of evil must be taken seriously, but the *potency* or *necessity* of evil need not be.\n\n*Derives from: Metaphysical Value-Judgments \u2014 humor is the denial of metaphysical significance; Sense of Life \u2014 what you find funny reflects your implicit metaphysics; Benevolent Universe Premise [ethics] \u2014 humor reinforces the benevolent universe premise*",
      "x": 2150,
      "y": 5700,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 420,
      "color": "6"
    },
    {
      "id": "aes-esthetic-objective",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "## Esthetic Value as Objective\n\nEsthetic value is neither \"in the object\" (intrinsicism) nor \"in the eye of the beholder\" (subjectivism). Beauty is *objective*: \"in the object \u2014 as judged by a rational beholder.\" Three esthetic principles define the standard:\n\n**1. Selectivity in regard to subject** \u2014 \"the primary, the essential, the cardinal aspect of art.\" The artist must make a conscious, rational choice of subject given his sense of life. No random, second-handed, or metaphysically meaningless subjects. Art devoid of meaning is devoid of esthetic value.\n\n**2. Clarity** \u2014 Art must be \"fully intelligible.\" The artist's function is to overcome the opacity of experience and reveal essence through judicious selectivity. Art must conform to the requirements of man's cognitive faculty \u2014 the rules identified by epistemology are not malleable to anyone's desires.\n\n**3. Integration** \u2014 \"The hallmark of art.\" Nothing accidental. Every item must be weighed against the theme and presented as an attribute of an indivisible whole. Anything insignificant destroys the spell \u2014 the integrity and power of the stylization. \"Nothing in this film is accidental\" \u2014 the motto of great art.\n\n**Nonobjective art** is to art what the arbitrary is to cognition: *anti-art.* It is the attempt not to re-create but to annihilate reality, not to integrate but to disintegrate consciousness.\n\n*Derives from: Art as Selective Re-Creation \u2014 selectivity is the cardinal principle; Psycho-Epistemological Function \u2014 art must conform to cognitive requirements; Objectivity [epistemology] \u2014 the method of objectivity applies to esthetic judgment; Values as Objective [ethics] \u2014 esthetic value is objective, like moral value*",
      "x": 1590,
      "y": 6300,
      "width": 520,
      "height": 460,
      "color": "3"
    },
    {
